Setting Up an XGA Video Adapter on a PS/2(R) Model 75 or 90
If you have a PS/2 model 75 or 90 with an XGA video adapter, Windows for
Workgroups Setup will configure the display adapter for 16-color, 640x480
resolution. Do not change this configuration during Setup. Specifying a
different XGA configuration while setting up Windows for Workgroups may
After you have successfully installed Windows, you can configure your XGA to
use a different resolution or 256 colors, if your monitor supports it. For
more information on how to do this, see the topic "IBM XGA: Configuring
Color and Resolution" in the README.WRI online document.
If you are using the plasma screen on the PS/2 model 75, use ONLY the
640x480, 16-color configuration. If you change this configuration, you
return to the MS-DOS prompt when you try to start Windows.
Setting up an IBM Token Ring 4/16Mbs Network Card on a Microchannel (MCA) Computer
If you have a Microchannel computer, and you are installing Windows for Workgroups
support for the IBM Token Ring 4/16Mbs network card, you must make sure the
Maximum Transmits parameter is set no higher than 1024. If you try to use a higher
value, the network card will not work with your computer.
Correcting the "Out of Environment Space" Error Message
If you receive an "out of environment space" message when starting Windows,
you can solve the problem in either of two ways:
*  Increase the size of your environment by adding the SHELL= command
line to your CONFIG.SYS file. See your MS-DOS documentation for more
information about the SHELL command and about modifying your CONFIG.SYS
*  Move the SET commands in your AUTOEXEC.BAT file to the beginning of
the file so that they run before the commands that load
terminate-and-stay-resident (TSR) programs or drivers, such as
Using Multimedia Extensions Version 1.0 with Windows for Workgroups
To use the Multimedia Extensions with Windows for Workgroups, first
set up Windows with Multimedia Extensions version 1.0. Then upgrade to
Windows for Workgroups by installing it into the same directory. If
you set up Windows for Workgroups before setting up Multimedia
Extensions, not all the files will be properly installed.
See the README.WRI online document for more information about running
Multimedia Extensions with Windows for Workgroups.

Setup adds Windows for Workgroups 3.11 to your copy of Windows. If you
have Windows version 3.0, Setup first upgrades it to version 3.1.
Upgrading preserves your WIN.INI file, along with any applications,
fonts, or drivers you may have. Only the Windows system files and
Upgrading to Windows for Workgroups 3.11 does the following:
* Maintains existing Program Manager groups -- If you have created
new groups in Program Manager, or added applications to existing
groups, Setup preserves those new groups or additions.
* Preserves existing System Information settings -- Current
selections for your computer, display, keyboard, mouse, keyboard
layout, language, and the associated drivers are preserved.
* Automatically updates existing Windows drivers -- If you have a
driver installed for which there is an updated 3.11 version,
Setup sets up the updated driver for you.
* Maintains all installed drivers that were not supplied with
Windows -- If you have a driver installed that was supplied by
another manufacturer, Setup leaves the driver unchanged.
* Preserves settings relating to the use of your system's upper-memory
area -- The order in which drivers are loaded in CONFIG.SYS is
critical in optimizing use of the upper-memory area. Setup
preserves the DEVICEHIGH= line and order existing in your

computer. Setup determines what kind of computer system you are using
and presents appropriate options for you to choose from during setup.

To return to Setup, press ESC.
Setup has two parts: an MS-DOS part and a Windows part.
You are now in the MS-DOS part of Setup. In this part,
* Identifies the type of computer, display, mouse, keyboard,
keyboard layout, language, and network you have.
* Confirms the directory where you will store the Windows files.
* Copies essential files to your hard disk so Setup can start
Setup gives you a chance to verify this information and change
specific settings before moving on to the next screen. After
completing the MS-DOS part, Setup starts Windows to set
up additional options and complete the setup process.
While running Setup, you may need to use various keys to move from

Windows provides two setup methods: Express Setup and Custom Setup.
Both are described in detail in the screens that follow.
With Express Setup, setting up Windows is simple and fast. You have
very few actions to perform, because Setup uses default settings and
does almost everything for you. Express Setup is recommended for
people who are less familiar with computers.
* Automatically configures your system. It detects your hardware
(computer, display, mouse, keyboard, keyboard layout, and language)
and sets it up for Windows. It modifies your AUTOEXEC.BAT and
CONFIG.SYS files to give Windows optimum performance.
* Selects a directory in which to set up Windows. Setup suggests
C:\WINDOWS if it is available. If Setup detects a copy of
Windows on your system, it asks if you want to add Windows for
Workgroups 3.11. If the copy of Windows is version 3.0, it
upgrades your copy of Windows to version 3.1 before adding
* Searches for adequate space on other local (not network) drives if
drive C is low on space.
* Recommends a partial setup if disk space is too low to set up the
full Windows system. Setup will propose setting up the most
important Windows components, and include others if more space is
* Helps you set up your printer, if you have one connected to your
computer or will have one on your network. Setup asks you for the
type of printer and the name of the port it is connected to.
* Automatically sets up applications for use with Windows. Setup
searches your path and hard drive(s) on your computer. It sets
up Windows-based applications and many MS-DOS--based applications.
* Offers a short tutorial on how to use the mouse, plus basic
Custom Setup is designed for users who want or need more control over
how Windows is set up on their computers. With Custom Setup, you
can override any default setup values, and you can choose which
Windows components and files you want copied to your hard disk. You
can also see and edit any changes made to your AUTOEXEC.BAT and
Custom Setup is recommended for users with more computer knowledge,
because it requires you to make several choices and to supply more
What You Need to Know for Custom Setup
To use Custom Setup, you must know how to use a mouse with
Windows. It also is helpful for you to know the following things
* What kind of computer (IBM or compatible) you have
* What kind of display (VGA or XGA) you have
* What kind of mouse (Microsoft or other) you have
* What kind of printer(s) you will be using
* Which port your printer is connected to
* What kind of keyboard you have
If you are not sure about any of these items, it is recommended that
you accept Setup's recommendations. Exception: If you do not have a
printer, select Printer, press ENTER, and then select No Printer.

Sets up Windows for Workgroups 3.11 on your system.
/N       - Sets up a shared copy of Windows for Workgroups from a network
/I       - Ignores hardware detection. During Setup, the user will need to
check accuracy of settings on the System Information screen,
/S:path  - Specifies a path to the setup disk(s).
/B       - Allows use of a monochrome monitor with a color graphics card.
/T       - Searches the drive for memory-resident (TSR) programs and
notifies you about certain programs. For information about
using specific programs with Setup or Windows for Workgroups,
/C       - Turns off the search for memory-resident (TSR) programs.
/A       - Administrative setup. Places Windows for Workgroups on a network
server. Setup expands and copies all files on every disk to a
given directory, and marks them read-only.
/H:file  - Batch mode setup. Sets up Windows for Workgroups with little or
no user interaction. "File" is the name of the system settings
file that contains user's configuration settings. If "file" is
not in the directory from which Windows for Workgroups is being
set up, the path must be included.
